def: Of or pertaining to the South Downs, a range of pasture hillssouth of the Thames, in England. Southdown sheep (Zo√∂l.), acelebrated breed of shortwooled, hornless sheep, highly valued onaccount of the delicacy of their flesh. So called from the SouthDowns where the breed originated.
Incapability of being mixed, or mingled.
To deprive of power; to divest of strength. H. Bushnell.
The act of burning, or the state of being burned. [R.] Johnson.
Long live, that is, success to; as, vive le roi, long live theking; vive la bagatelle, success to trifles or sport.
Predicating; affirming; declaring; proclaiming; hence;preaching. "The Roman predicant orders." N. Brit. Rev.

An ornamental tree of the genus Maclura (M. aurantiaca),closely allied to the mulberry (Morus); also, its fruit. The tree wasfirst found in the country of the Osage Indians, and bears a hard andinedible fruit of an orangelike appearance. See Bois d'arc.
The quality or state of being tumid.
